  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Assessment of housing conditions and other socioeconomic determinants of Tuberculosis among dwellers in urban slum communities in Uganda</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Uganda&apos;s rapid urban population growth, driven in part by the resettlement of internally displaced people from camps in the north, has resulted in several densely populated and poorly planned slum settlements. The sub-standard, cramped living conditions in these areas, coupled with poor health services, are particularly conducive to the spread of Tuberculosis (TB), which is also fuelled by the high prevalence of HIV. Target Tuberculosis is assessing the lack of knowledge about TB in three contrasting slum communities in Uganda and developing strategies to address the prevention, diagnosis and treatment of TB, and better understand the link with HIV/AIDS. By involving slum residents directly the project has a strong community empowerment, motivating community members to take control of and address their own health needs. The project also helps to improve slum-dwellers&apos; rights to health care.</narrative>
  </description>
